Accor, Akzo Nobel, Allianz, Nutreco, Volkswagen AG: Europe Equity Preview

-- B y   I n y o u n g   H w a n g
-- 
2011-04-21T04:00:04Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-20/accor-akzo-nobel-allianz-nutreco-volkswagen-ag-europe-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index rose 1.7 percent to 279.06. The
Stoxx 50 Index advanced 1.7 percent to 2,613.36. The Euro Stoxx
50 Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, climbed 2.2
percent to 2,921.43.  Accor SA (AC)  : Europe’s largest hotel company said
first-quarter sales rose 5.8 percent and confirmed its objective
of opening 30,000 new rooms in 2011. Accor rose 2.6 percent to
31.45 euros.  Akzo Nobel NV (AKZA)  : The world’s biggest paint maker
may say first-quarter net income rose to 105 million euros ($152
million), the average of 12 analyst estimates compiled by
Bloomberg, from 81 million euros a year earlier. Akzo Nobel
gained 1.8 percent to 50.45 euros.  Allianz AG (ALV GY),  Munich Re  (MUV2 GY): German insurers
would be able to handle a restructuring of  Greece ’s debt as the
industry’s total capital investment in the country was 4.9
billion euros ($7.1 billion) as of Sept. 30, Handelsblatt
reported, citing figures from  Germany ’s finance ministry.
Allianz rose 2.3 percent to 101.20 euros, while Munich Re added
1.6 percent to 115.20 euros.  Banca Popolare di Milano Scrl (PMI IM): Shares of the
Milan-based cooperative bank were cut to “underweight” from
“buy” at Banco Santander SA. The stock dropped 8.6 percent to
2.31 euros.  Bayerische Motoren Werke AG (BMW)  : The world’s largest
luxury-vehicle maker may spend less on sales incentives in the
U.S. because production disruptions in  Japan  may reduce the
supply of competing luxury vehicles available. Its shares rose 3
percent to 60.53 euros.  Nutreco NV (NUO)  : The world’s biggest maker of fish feed
is scheduled to give a trading update before the start of
trading. Nutreco increased 0.9 percent to 53.58 euros.  Schneider Electric SA (SU)  : The world’s biggest maker of
low- and medium-voltage equipment damped speculation that it is
exploring a major purchase, saying it prefers smaller deals and
that no large-scale transaction is in the pipeline for 2011. The
company also said first-quarter sales rose 27 percent, led by
demand in  Asia . The stock rose 2.3 percent to 114.25 euros.  Volkswagen AG (VOW)  (VOW3 GY): The car maker’s Audi luxury brand
is considering options for assembling some vehicles in the U.S.
The shares gained 4.8 percent to 118.40 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
